    <patterns>
      <pattern name="useChatFileAttachment chip lifecycle" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/hooks/useChatFileAttachment.ts">
        Hook produces `files: AttachmentChip[]` with `status: 'extracting' | 'ready' | 'error'`, plus a derived `attachments: ChatAttachment[]` of ready chips for the outbound payload, plus `removeFile(index)` + `clearAll()`. R5 extends the CONSUMER (ConversationPane) — does NOT modify the hook signature or add new state inside the hook.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="handleAttachmentReady Workspace dispatch (R4 task 042 / W-4)" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/ConversationPane.tsx (~L611)">
        Existing callback fires once per ready file, dispatches `widget_load` on the `workspace` channel with a typed `DocumentViewerWidgetData` payload. R5 PARALLELS this with a new `context.files_staged` dispatch — does NOT replace it. The existing R4 behaviour MUST be regression-tested.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="PaneEventBus dispatch with typed payload" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/ConversationPane.tsx (~L618)">
        Use the `dispatch` callback from `usePaneEventBus()` (already imported in ConversationPane). Pass a typed payload object discriminated by `type`. Per ADR-030: no `any` at the dispatch boundary; cast to the typed shape from `PaneEventTypes.ts`. The `context.files_staged` event type is defined in task 016's deliverable.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Fluent v9 semantic-token styling + dark mode" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/ConversationPane.tsx (makeStyles block)">
        Follow the existing `makeStyles({...})` block. Use `tokens.colorNeutralForeground2` (or equivalent) for the indicator text; never raw hex. Test dark mode by toggling the host theme (the SpaarkeAi shell wraps in `FluentProvider` with light/dark theme switching — verify the indicator + chip strip still meet contrast requirements).
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Inline local message convention (client-rendered, non-model)" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/types.ts">
        Locate the existing SprkChat message type. If it exposes a `role: 'system' | 'assistant' | 'user'` or `kind: 'local' | 'streamed'` discriminator suitable for a client-rendered confirmation, reuse it. Otherwise, extend the existing message-injection helper (e.g., a `predefinedPrompts`-style injection or a sibling helper) to allow R5 to push a one-shot local message. Document the choice in task notes; do NOT introduce a parallel message store.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Deterministic interjection emission (once per turn)" location="src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/ConversationPane.tsx (new)">
        Track interjection emission via a `useRef&lt;Set&lt;string&gt;&gt;` keyed by the chat turn id (or by a stable hash of file IDs + send-attempt counter). On each summarize-turn boundary, check the ref before emitting; mark emitted after first emission. Reset on session change. This guarantees "exactly once per multi-file summary turn" semantics across stream resumption / retry.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships a chat-driven "Summarize a Document" vertical slice. The user uploads
      up to 5 files per turn (`useChatFileAttachment` cap) and up to 20 files per
      session (`ChatSession.UploadedFiles[]` server cap per NFR-02). The chat pane
      MUST surface that file state without forcing the user to leave the chat thread
      to inspect or manage attached files. R3 already shipped the chip strip via
      `useChatFileAttachment`; R4 task 042 (W-4) wired the first-file Workspace
      dispatch via `handleAttachmentReady`. R5 closes the loop:

      - the user sees a persistent "N files attached" indicator (no more wondering
        what the server thinks is in scope);
      - the user can remove a file directly from chat, with cascade to the server
        manifest AND the `spaarke-session-files` index (no orphaned index docs);
      - the user gets in-thread confirmation when files become ready ("I have your
        3 files: ...");
      - multi-file summarize requests get a clarifying interjection BEFORE the
        model response begins ("I'll combine all 3 files into a single summary"),
        so the user understands that "Summarize this" means a COMBINED summary,
        not per-file summaries (per FR-08 single-file affordance lives separately
        via the per-file "Summarize this only" button — task 021).
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="017" status="not-started">D2-07 StructuredOutputStreamWidget — chat-pane interjections may reference structured-output rendering for the model response that follows. Soft dependency: this task wires the interjection emission point; 017 owns the model response surface. The interjection itself does NOT depend on 017's widget being present (it's pure local chat text).</dependency>
      <dependency task="016" status="not-started">D2-06 PaneEventBus event types — the `context.files_staged` event type definition lands in task 016. This task DISPATCHES the event; 016 defines the type. Sequencing: 016 should land first (parallel-safe within P2-G3); if 016 is incomplete when this task starts, coordinate via a temporary local type cast and surface a follow-up to consolidate.</dependency>
      <dependency task="004" status="phase-1">D1-04 ChatSession.UploadedFiles[] manifest — server manifest contract; this task calls the manifest-remove path. Phase 1 must be complete.</dependency>
      <dependency task="007" status="phase-1">D1-07 SessionFilesCleanupJob — provides the session-files index document removal path; this task INVOKES that path (either via cleanup endpoint or BFF-side facade). Phase 1 must be complete.</dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>Task 019 (D2-10) — Slash command `/summarize` semantic extension. Parallel wave-mate (P2-G5); shares the multi-file-routing logic. Coordinate on the interjection emission point so both code paths (slash command + free-text) route through the same emission helper.</item>
      <item>Task 021 (D2-12) — Per-file "Summarize this only" affordance. Parallel wave-mate; lives in `FilePreviewContextWidget` (Context pane), NOT the chat pane. The chat-pane interjection in this task addresses the COMBINED-summary case; 021 owns the single-file case.</item>
      <item>Task 022 (D2-08 follow-up) — DocumentViewerWidget upgrade. Parallel wave-mate; uses the extracted `RichFilePreview` renderer. No direct coupling, but both tasks touch ConversationPane indirectly via shared file lifecycle.</item>
      <item>R4 task 042 (W-4) `handleAttachmentReady` — existing R4 Workspace dispatch; this task EXTENDS without regressing.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Context Check + RIGOR LEVEL Declaration">
      Check context usage. If &gt; 70%, run `context-handoff` and request `/compact`.
      Output mandatory rigor-level declaration per CLAUDE.md §8:
      ```
      🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: FULL
      📋 REASON: Frontend (.tsx) on critical path; PaneEventBus dispatch (ADR-030);
         dark-mode + Fluent v9 token compliance (ADR-021); React 19 (ADR-022); shared
         component boundary discipline (ADR-012); cross-task coordination with 016 +
         019; new test coverage required (project CLAUDE.md §3.7).
      📖 PROTOCOL STEPS TO EXECUTE: Steps 1–10 below with code-review + adr-check at 9.5.
      Proceeding with Step 0...
      ```
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Review Progress">
      Read `tasks/TASK-INDEX.md` and confirm: task 020 status is 🔲, wave P2-G5,
      parallel-safe = ✅, dependencies = 017. Confirm Phase 1 tasks (004, 007) are ✅
      and task 016 (PaneEventBus event types) status — if 016 is still 🔲, decide
      whether to wait or coordinate via temporary type cast (document in notes).
      Read `current-task.md` to confirm scope. Read project README for status.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Gather Resources">
      Read every file in &lt;inputs&gt; + &lt;knowledge&gt;. Specifically:
      (a) Read `ConversationPane.tsx` end-to-end so you understand the existing
          callback wiring (`handleAttachmentReady`, `dispatch`, `setChatSessionId`,
          etc.) and the existing makeStyles block.
      (b) Read `useChatFileAttachment.ts` to confirm the chip/attachments/removeFile
          API surface — do NOT modify this hook.
      (c) Read `SprkChat.tsx` to identify the chip strip render location (~L2076) and
          the in-flight attachment send wiring (~L942).
      (d) Read the spec.md sections on FR-03 (prompt-first path), FR-07 (chip lifecycle),
          NFR-02 (20-file cap), and ADR-030 event-type discipline.
      (e) Read related-task POMLs 004, 007, 016, 017, 019, 021 to understand contract
          boundaries.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Confirm Cleanup Pathway (manifest + index)">
      Decide the cascade path for per-file remove:
      - **Manifest remove**: identify the BFF endpoint or `@spaarke/auth`-authenticated
        client call established by task 004 (D1-04) for removing one file from
        `ChatSession.UploadedFiles[]`. If task 004 ships only the model + read path,
        document the gap and propose either: (a) a small DELETE endpoint
        `DELETE /api/ai/chat/sessions/{sessionId}/files/{fileId}` (preferred — minimal
        BFF surface, idempotent, returns updated manifest), OR (b) a manifest-update
        PATCH variant. Decide and record in task notes; coordinate with task 004
        owner if scope shift required (escalate per CLAUDE.md §6 if endpoint must be
        added).
      - **Index cleanup**: identify the path task 007 (D1-07) exposes for removing
        a specific session-files index document by `SearchDocumentIdsCsv` entry.
        Per task 007, the cleanup service runs as `IHostedService` for session-end
        sweeps but exposes a method (likely `RemoveDocumentsAsync(sessionId, docIds)`
        or equivalent) reachable via a small DELETE endpoint or by piggy-backing on
        the manifest-remove endpoint (preferred: have the manifest-remove endpoint
        invoke the index removal internally as a single transactional call so the
        frontend issues ONE HTTP call per user action).
      Document the chosen pathway in task notes. Confirm BFF publish-size = 0 MB IF
      the path is purely frontend-consumable (manifest-remove endpoint already exists);
      flag delta if a new tiny endpoint is added.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Plan Implementation">
      Break into subtasks (silent checkpoint after each):
      4.1 Add "N files attached" indicator render to ConversationPane (or pass through
          to SprkChat — choose location based on SprkChat surface inspection).
      4.2 Wire per-file remove cascade: chip remove → BFF manifest+index call →
          local `removeFile(index)` after server confirms (or optimistic update with
          rollback on failure).
      4.3 Wire inline confirmation message emission on `attachment.status === 'ready'`
          transitions; ensure single-emission-per-upload-turn via debounce / ref.
      4.4 Wire deterministic multi-file interjection emission on summarize-turn
          boundary (coordinate with task 019's slash-command intent handler if it
          owns the turn-entry point).
      4.5 Add `context.files_staged` PaneEventBus dispatch on ready transitions
          (parallel to existing `workspace.widget_load` dispatch — keep R4 behaviour).
      4.6 Dark mode + a11y verification.
      4.7 Tests (RTL + Jest) per project CLAUDE.md §3.7.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Implement Indicator + Chip Wiring">
      Implement subtasks 4.1 + 4.2:
      - Render the "N files attached" indicator using Fluent `Text` or a small
        `Tag` with `tokens.colorNeutralForeground2` semantic token. Bind to the
        active `ChatSession.UploadedFiles.length` (preferred) OR
        `attachments.length` from the hook if the session-manifest read is not yet
        available client-side (document the choice). Hide when count = 0.
      - Wire `removeFile(index)` to ALSO call the cleanup pathway from Step 3.
        Use an optimistic-update pattern: call `removeFile(index)` immediately for
        snappy UX, then make the HTTP call; on failure, surface a Fluent toast +
        re-add the chip (the hook does not expose `addFiles(...)` for a single
        already-extracted chip, so a small `addBackChip(chip)` helper may be needed
        — keep it inside ConversationPane, NOT in `@spaarke/ui-components`).
      Run silent checkpoint after this step.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Implement Inline Confirmations + Interjection + PaneEventBus Dispatch">
      Implement subtasks 4.3 + 4.4 + 4.5:
      - Track ready-transition events using a `useRef&lt;Set&lt;string&gt;&gt;` keyed by
        chip `id`. When a chip transitions from `extracting` → `ready`, check the
        ref; if not seen, emit a local inline confirmation message via the SprkChat
        message-injection helper. Debounce simultaneous arrivals into a single
        "I have your N files: a, b, c" message (e.g., a 250ms tail-end debounce).
      - On summarize-turn entry where `UploadedFiles.length &gt; 1`: emit the
        deterministic interjection BEFORE the model response begins. Coordinate
        the emission point with task 019's intent handler; the helper itself should
        live in a shared `SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/` helper so both
        the slash-command path and the free-text path call it.
      - Dispatch `context.files_staged` on the ready transition:
        ```ts
        dispatch("context", {
          type: "files_staged",
          fileIds: readyChipIds,
          sessionId: chatSessionId,
        });
        ```
        Use the typed payload from `PaneEventTypes.ts` (task 016). Do NOT use `any`.
        Preserve the existing `handleAttachmentReady` Workspace dispatch — both
        events fire on the same trigger but on DIFFERENT channels.
      Run silent checkpoint after this step.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Dark Mode + A11y Verification">
      Toggle the SpaarkeAi shell theme (light → dark → light). Verify:
      - "N files attached" indicator readable in both themes (contrast ratio &gt;= 4.5:1
        per WCAG AA).
      - Chip remove button keyboard-accessible (Tab + Enter / Space).
      - Inline confirmation message has appropriate `role` / `aria-live` attribute
        (use the existing SprkChat message rendering — no new ARIA primitive).
      - Multi-file interjection rendered with the same a11y treatment as other
        local chat messages.
      Capture before/after screenshots for task notes (light + dark).
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Tests">
      Add Jest + RTL tests colocated with `ConversationPane.tsx` (or under
      `src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/conversation/__tests__/`). Cover:
      - Indicator renders + reactively updates on add/remove.
      - Per-file remove dispatches manifest + index cleanup call (mock HTTP);
        on success removes chip; on failure restores chip + shows toast.
      - Inline confirmation message emits once per ready batch (debounced).
      - Multi-file interjection emits exactly once per turn (verify via repeated
        retry / stream-resumption scenarios).
      - PaneEventBus `context.files_staged` dispatch fires with correct typed payload.
      - R4 regression: `workspace.widget_load` for first ready file STILL fires.
      Aim for ≥ 90% line coverage on the new code paths. Run `npm test --workspace
      SpaarkeAi` (or the project's equivalent) and confirm green.
    </step>
    <step order="9" name="Verify Acceptance Criteria">
      Walk through every &lt;acceptance-criterion&gt; below; record evidence per
      criterion in task notes. Run a full build of SpaarkeAi
      (`npm run build --workspace SpaarkeAi`) and confirm no TypeScript errors and
      no Fluent / React 19 warnings. Confirm BFF publish-size delta = 0 MB
      (frontend-only task; no BFF code modified — unless Step 3 surfaced a tiny new
      endpoint, in which case measure delta and confirm &lt; +0.5 MB).
    </step>
    <step order="9.5" name="Quality Gates (FULL rigor)">
      Run `code-review` skill against the modified files (ConversationPane.tsx +
      any helper + tests). Run `adr-check` skill; verify: ADR-012 (shared lib
      boundary — no SpaarkeAi imports leaked into @spaarke/ui-components), ADR-021
